One bad dive in the Men's 10-Meter synchronized platform caused the Chinese men's diving team to lose the gold metal by a very close margin: https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/diving/results-men-s-synchronised-10m-platform-fnl-000100-.htm They dominated the remainder of the other dives. Team GB had a great performance!
China at 88% seems too high. Odds seem to imply that it should be closer to 60%. GB at 15% or so. Rest farther behind.

Increasing chances for China to win [https://apnews.com/article/china-tokyo-diving-olympic-games-2020-tokyo-olympics-fa6cbe630d4cda26a12a08b503fdb101]; however, it is worth noting that the composition of China's synchronized 3-meter springboard diving team has changed from the 2019 World Championships.

More than a 1% chance that the event doesn't happen, but not 2%. China historically; thanks to @the_trumpet_vine for the links. The shifts between Mexico, Germany, Russia in recent international competitions indicates that silver can be noisy.

Aggregating other comments (especially the one from @clewey who's convincing / quasi-exhaustive + other comments that suggest that US has a shot aswell), I reached this point where China are the most likely, Great Britain the second ones and US seems to have a chance.

China has dominated diving at the world championships and Olympics. If we use the last five olympics, China has won 3 gold metals, with Great Britain winning one, as well as Greece. At the same time Russia has won 3 silver metals (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Olympic_medalists_in_diving#Synchronized_3_metre_springboard). Let's assume base rates of 60% for China, with 20% for Great Britain and 20% for Greece.
